      "id":"politics/2013/nov/08/jeremy-hunt-17m-hotcourses-sale-inflexion",
      "sectionId":"politics",
      "sectionName":"Politics",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-08T20:35:48Z",
      "webTitle":"Jeremy Hunt could net £17m if pre-politics business sells",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/nov/08/jeremy-hunt-17m-hotcourses-sale-inflexion",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/politics/2013/nov/08/jeremy-hunt-17m-hotcourses-sale-inflexion",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"10",
        "trailText":"Hotcourses' sale to Inflexion would propel health secretary into the ranks of most successful entrepreneurs in the Commons",
        "headline":"Jeremy Hunt could net £17m if pre-politics business sells",
        "body":"<p>Jeremy Hunt could be in line for a windfall of up to £17m should Hotcourses, the online directory of courses he founded 17 years ago, be sold to Inflexion, the private equity firm behind the Jack Wills preppy clothing brand.</p><p>The proposed deal, valuing the whole company at about £35m, would cement the health secretary's reputation as one of the most successful entrepreneurs in the House of Commons.</p><p>Other wealthy figures in the cabinet include defence secretary Philip Hammond, who made millions in nursing homes and other ventures. David Cameron and George Osborne were also rated among the most wealthy in a study last year by Wealth-X, though in both case their riches were largely inherited.</p><p>Although Hunt stepped down as a director of Hotcourses in 2009, he is still the largest shareholder, with a 49% stake. His interest in the firm is held via a \"blind trust\" which means he is prevented from having any day to day control of his stake.</p><p>Inflexion is understood to be in a period of exclusive discussions over an acquisition of the business, although it is not certain whether a sale will go through. Hunt, Hotcourses and Inflexion did not reply or declined to comment.</p><p>The firm, which went by the name Elms Hunt International until 2001, is still run by the health secretary's childhood friend and co-founder, Mike Elms. The latest accounts show the business made a pre-tax profit of £2m on a turnover of £6.5m for the seven months to July 2012. Elms said that represented a 17% rise in sales and a jump in profits of more than 50%.</p><p>One of Hotcourses' biggest contracts is a deal to run a website for the British Council, promoting courses in the UK. The council is a quango sponsored by the Foreign Office to promote cultural and educational opportunities abroad. It is part-funded by government grants.</p><p>Hunt has insisted the success of Hotcourses came only after Elms and he had pursued a string of failed ventures. Among their false starts were a scheme to export marmalade to Japan, building children's playgrounds and a tourist guide idea. The two businessmen had also set up a political PR firm, Profile PR, later renamed Heckler, in the early 1990s.</p><p>Hunt has recalled how the pair eventually stumbled on the winning formula that became Hotcourses after they had been publishing student university guides, quickly spotting it as a bigger business opportunity.</p><p>On his website, Hunt reminds his constituents in South West Surrey that he understands the hardship of starting up a new business.</p><p>\"A lot of people who start their own business do so because they think it's a good way to make a lot of money, but when you start it becomes simply a matter of survival. It's a daily struggle, which is why small business people tend to be very down to earth and practical.\"</p><p>The eldest son of Admiral Sir Nicholas Hunt, the health secretary was educated at Charterhouse private school and Magdalen College, Oxford, before turning to business and latterly politics.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/422050864|2013-11-12T10:05:52Z|e3d4284527cdc15d6483493f506cc93b58f80e8a -->",
